‚Üí #‚Üďt #‚Üďt #‚Üďt #‚Üďt @









   @   @   @   @

  sisobus
  ----------------------------------------------------------------------
  Five winds blow simultaneously across the grid.

  Output:  empty.  Exit 0.

  This program never prints anything. It exists to exhibit Windy's
  multi-IP machinery: at peak the runtime juggles five live IPs
  in parallel, each tracing its own path before halting at its own
  `@`.

  How it works
  ------------
  Row 0 has four `t` SPLIT cells. The parent IP enters going east
  and crosses them in sequence. After each `t` the live IP list
  grows by one ‚ÄĒ a fresh child spawned at (parent_x ‚ąí 1, 0) going
  west. Four splits = five total IPs (1 parent + 4 children).

  Cascade avoidance
  -----------------
  Two design tricks keep the splits clean:

  1. `#` (TRAMPOLINE) before each `t`. The parent reads `#`,
     skips the next cell, and lands on `t`. The cell that gets
     skipped is always `‚Üď` ‚ÄĒ that's deliberate.
  2. `‚Üď` at every (col_t ‚ąí 1) position. When the child reads its
     first cell (the one it spawned on), it sees `‚Üď`, sets its
     direction to south, and immediately leaves row 0 for row 1.
     It never re-traverses the row of `t`s, so no child re-fires
     SPLIT and the population can't snowball.

  The parent uses `#` to *skip* the `‚Üď` cells so they don't
  redirect *parent* south ‚ÄĒ only children, on their way out.

  After the four splits the parent continues east, falls off
  into one final `@` at (18, 0), and halts.

  The four children
  -----------------
  Each child spawns at columns 3, 7, 11, 15 (=col_t ‚ąí 1), heads
  south down its own column, and crosses ten blank rows before
  hitting an `@` waiting for it on row 10:

      col 3   col 7   col 11   col 15
       ‚Ēā        ‚Ēā         ‚Ēā         ‚Ēā
       ‚Üď        ‚Üď         ‚Üď         ‚Üď
       (drift through 9 rows of NOP space)
       ‚Üď        ‚Üď         ‚Üď         ‚Üď
       @        @         @         @     <- row 10

  The four `@`s on row 10 line up exactly under each child's
  spawn column. Each child halts independently; there are no
  collisions and no merges.

  Tick-by-tick IP count
  ---------------------
    tick 0‚Äď3   : 1 (parent only)
    tick 4     : 2 (child1 born by `t` at col 4)
    tick 7     : 3 (child2 born at col 8)
    tick 10    : 4 (child3 born at col 12)
    tick 13    : 5 ‚Üź peak, all four children alive at once
    tick 14    : 5 (parent still alive, all four children still
                    descending)
    tick 15    : 3 (parent halts at @ on col 18; child1 halts at
                    its @ on row 10)
    tick 18    : 2 (child2 halts)
    tick 21    : 1 (child3 halts)
    tick 24    : 0 (child4 halts; live IP list empty ‚Üí program ends)

  Things to notice
  ----------------
  - Step under `windy debug examples/winds.wnd`. Watch the
    `ips:` row in the state panel climb: 1 ‚Üí 2 ‚Üí 3 ‚Üí 4 ‚Üí 5,
    then drain back down to 0. The grid view highlights every
    live IP cell, so the descending columns are visible at once.

  - The blank rows in the source aren't padding ‚ÄĒ they are the
    children's actual flight paths, drawn into the grid as
    empty space. Each child crosses ten of those rows before
    landing on its `@`.

  - Try changing one of the `‚Üď` cells to a space. That child
    will go west off the grid instead, drift forever, and
    --max-steps will fire. The `‚Üď` redirects are what bound
    the children's lifetimes.
